      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "security: add Security Matrix runtime-fact audit model",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Adds a Security Matrix runtime-fact evaluator.\n- Models actor, influence source, tool capability, approval state, and operator policy as separate inputs.\n- Adds default policy data, a deterministic evaluator, tool capability resolution, an audit-event object builder, tests, and documentation.\n- Adds a before-tool-call fact adapter and anchors it to the trusted tool policy boundary through an inert audit-event builder.\n- Removes the unsupported `security.matrix.audit.enabled` placeholder so this PR does not reserve a parallel config surface.\n- Removes the Security Matrix production files from the required dead-code allowlist; they are now in the optional allowlist since the model is not yet wired into the runtime import graph.\n- Hardens custom policy parsing so malformed decisions cannot weaken the default policy.\n\n## Scope\n\nThis PR remains non-enforcing and observe-only.\n\nIt does not block tool calls, require confirmation at runtime, emit runtime diagnostic events, change UI, change plugin behavior, or alter runtime tool execution. The before-tool-call adapter only builds an audit event object from explicit boundary facts. Runtime diagnostic emission, canonical config, CLI display, and enforcement remain future work.\n\nNo default trusted `security_matrix.evaluated` log records are emitted. The adapter is a pure function that builds the audit event shape; no runtime diagnostic wiring is included.\n\n## Changes since last review\n\n- Removed Security Matrix production files from the **required** `KNIP_UNUSED_FILE_ALLOWLIST` (which would fail as stale once the files are reachable). They are now in `KNIP_OPTIONAL_UNUSED_FILE_ALLOWLIST` since the model is not yet wired into the production import graph.\n- Clarified docs: the before-tool-call adapter defaults `approvalState` to `not_required`, while the low-level evaluator normalizes missing/undefined to `none`.\n- No runtime diagnostic emission was added. The `trusted-tool-policy.ts` path does not import or call the Security Matrix adapter.\n\n## Validation\n\nLatest head: `b8f3e69aa3`.\n\nFocused commands run against this head:\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\npnpm test src/security/security-matrix/evaluate.test.ts\npnpm changed:lanes --base upstream/main --json\npnpm exec oxlint src/security/security-matrix/ src/plugins/trusted-tool-policy.ts\nnode scripts/format-docs.mjs --check docs/security/security-matrix.md\ngit diff --check upstream/main...HEAD\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior addressed: Security Matrix runtime-fact evaluation produces deterministic audit decisions from actor, influence source, capability, approval state, and operator policy. The before-tool-call adapter builds the same audit-event shape from explicit boundary facts without emitting, blocking, or mutating execution. Malformed custom policy decisions are ignored instead of being treated as policy output.\n\nReal environment tested: Local OpenClaw development environment (Node.js 22, pnpm, Linux). The Security Matrix evaluator and before-tool-call adapter were exercised through the unit test suite and lint/typecheck passes.\n\nExact commands and output:\n\n\\`\\`\\`\n$ CI=true pnpm test src/security/security-matrix/evaluate.test.ts\n RUN  v4.1.7\n ✓  unit-fast  src/security/security-matrix/evaluate.test.ts (27 tests) 13ms\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  27 passed (27)\n   Duration  266ms\n\n$ pnpm changed:lanes --base upstream/main --json\n{\n  \"lanes\": { \"core\": true, \"coreTests\": true, \"extensions\": false, ... }\n}\n\n$ pnpm exec oxlint src/security/security-matrix/ src/plugins/trusted-tool-policy.ts\nFound 0 warnings and 0 errors.\nFinished in 25ms on 8 files with 208 rules using 8 threads.\n\n$ node scripts/format-docs.mjs --check docs/security/security-matrix.md\nDocs formatting clean (663 files).\n\n$ git diff --check upstream/main...HEAD\n(no whitespace errors)\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nObserved result: All 27 Security Matrix unit tests pass, lint passes with 0 warnings/errors, docs formatting is clean, and no whitespace errors. The required `KNIP_UNUSED_FILE_ALLOWLIST` is empty; Security Matrix production files are in the optional allowlist. No runtime diagnostic emission was added.\n\nWhat was not tested: Runtime hook emission, runtime enforcement, strict config schema adoption, CLI display, plugin UI, and live tool execution are intentionally not changed by this PR.",
